So for example, if we&rsquo;re looking at the United States the country <strong>we would normally use the singular verb</strong> so for example &ndash; &ldquo;The United States is a very big country.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
However, if we&rsquo;re thinking about the government in the United States we might want to use a plural noun - &ldquo;The United States are a major power in the World.&rdquo; This singular plural difference is one that we see reflected in a number of other nouns in English. For example, when we&rsquo;re talking about the government we can say &ndash; &ldquo;The government has won the election.&rdquo; Or we can say &ldquo;The government have won the election.&rdquo; <strong>This depends if we see the government as a collection of individuals</strong> - &ldquo;The government have won the election.&rdquo; &ndash; or if we see the government as one thing - &ldquo;The government has won the election.&rdquo;

